Okay, let me play theologian's advocate <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :intel --><img src=http://heartjoys.fcpages.com/Sparrow'sHearth/znaika.gif ALT=":intel"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  (the devil does not any advocate!).<br>
<br>
It isn't a simple case of God choosing first, then we choose him. Rather the choosing is of a different kind. The passage in context (Joshua 24) is not a &quot;decision for Jesus&quot; scenario (excuse the anachronism <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :fsl --><img src=http://heartjoys.fcpages.com/Sparrow'sHearth/fallasleep.gif ALT=":fsl"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> , but you get the idea). The Israelites were already the people of God; they now faced the future as to where their allegiance lay (&quot;those other gods or the God who led you from the wilderness to the promised land&quot;). Their &quot;choosing&quot; wasn't a &quot;coming to faith&quot; nor even a &quot;maturity in faith&quot; statement.<br>
<br>
Okay, theologian's clarification duly noted. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :amen --><img src=http://heartjoys.fcpages.com/Sparrow'sHearth/amen.gif ALT=":amen"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
For me, I was raised in the church, baptized at 6 months, which was a valid baptism since was doing it, and then grew up through the expect hoops of the 1950's- mid 1960's. My two grandmothers had tremendous impact on all three of us boys. My older brother is a Christian psychologist, my younger brother has been an elder and church leader for 15 years, and then me.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :fsl --><img src=http://heartjoys.fcpages.com/Sparrow'sHearth/fallasleep.gif ALT=":fsl"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
In college I worshipped with my girlfriend on the weekends, because she did, and continued when we were engaged and eventually married. My heart was not &quot;evil&quot; but I had drifted.<br>
<br>
For me a major turning point came when as a naval officer <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :usa --><img src=http://www.geocities.com/bat3193/smiley14/usa.gif ALT=":usa"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  I was standing at the edge of the jungle outside the Officer's Club at Cubi Point, Philippines at 3:00 AM contemplating why I had a drink in one hand (and had since 8:00 PM the night before), and a newspaper article in the other hand about how other naval officers had helped build an orphage in the mountains of the Philippines. I threw the glass into the jungle, and began a slow process of examining who God was and who I was. Within six years I was at seminary, and now 20+ years later, well... look where I am - writing on a message board. <p>In Christ,<br>
